"Larsen J.B.","Ecological stability of forests and sustainable silviculture",1995,"Forest Ecology and Management","73","1-3",,"85","96",,,10.1016/0378-1127(94)03501-M,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0028972486&partnerID=40&md5=920c6294081d3656ac02065370002bf1","Unit of Forestry, The Royal Veterinary and Agricultural University, Thorvaldsensvej 57, DK-1871 Frederiksberg C, Denmark","Larsen, J.B., Unit of Forestry, The Royal Veterinary and Agricultural University, Thorvaldsensvej 57, DK-1871 Frederiksberg C, Denmark","The ecological stability of forests is described and subsequently analyzed and discussed in relation to human impact. Forest management and utilization have a considerable influence on the stability and sustainability of forest ecosystems. Additionally, other human activities such as pollution and global climate change affect the present and future stability of our forests. The main components of stability are resistance (inertia, immovability) and resilience (recoverability). These are analyzed with respect to genetic diversity within and between species and in relation to the biogeochemical cycle. The possibilities and constraints of silviculture are then discussed in relation to sustainable management practices and strategies, i.e. choice of provenances and species, including species mixtures, tree breeding, harvesting practices, as well as the silvicultural system applied. Finally, forest decline is discussed in relation to stability by means of a stress integration model. © 1995.","Biogeochemical cycle; Ecological stability; Forest decline; Forest ecosystem; Genetic variation; Management; Silviculture; Sustainability","biogeochemical cycle; ecological stability; forestry production; human impact; silviculture; sustainable forestry",,,,,,"Ackzell, Lindgren, Some genetic aspects on human intervention in forest regeneration—Considerations based on examples from an experiment in northern Sweden (1994) Forestry, 67, pp. 133-148; Amara